# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: environment-and-climate-change-canada
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2011-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The **2011 United Nations Climate Change Conference** (COP17) was held in Durban, South Africa, from 28 November to 11 December 2011 to establish a new treaty to limit carbon emissions.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2011-united-nations-climate-change-conference] A treaty was not established, but the conference agreed to establish a legally binding deal comprising all countries by 2015, which was to take effect in 2020.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2011-united-nations-climate-change-conference] There was also progress regarding the creation of a Green Climate Fund for which a management framework was adopted.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2011-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The fund is to distribute US$100 billion per year to help poor countries adapt to climate impacts.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2011-united-nations-climate-change-conference] While the president of the conference, Maite Nkoana-Mashabane, declared it a success, scientists and environmental groups warned that the deal was not sufficient to avoid global warming beyond 2 °C as more urgent action is needed.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2011-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The conference was officially referred to as the 17th session of the Conference of the Parties (COP 17) to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC) and the 7th session of the Conference of the Parties serving as the meeting of the Parties (CMP 7) to the Kyoto Protocol.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2011-united-nations-climate-change-conference] In addition, the two permanent subsidiary bodies of the UNFCCC – the Subsidiary Body for Scientific and Technological Advice (SBSTA) and the Subsidiary Body for Implementation (SBI) – were likely to hold their 35th sessions.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2011-united-nations-climate-change-conference] A primary focus of the conference was to secure a global climate agreement as the Kyoto Protocol's first commitment period (2008–2012) was about to end.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2011-united-nations-climate-change-conference] A month before the Conference began, the BBC highlighted two contentious proposals which had been submitted – one by Russia, the other by Papua New Guinea, both aiming to amend the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2011-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Russia's proposal would bring about a "periodic review" whereby countries currently categorised as "poor" could be recategorised as "rich", and thus obliged to shoulder greater obligations in the combat against climate change.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2011-united-nations-climate-change-conference] BBC Environment correspondent Richard Black commented that the proposal would be "provocative and explosive, if Russia pushes it", because potentially affected countries, such as China and Brazil, would "push back very strongly".
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2011-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Papua New Guinea's proposal, submitted by Ambassador Kevin Conrad with the support of Mexico, would introduce a "last resort" mechanism to break any deadlocks in climate change negotiations through a three-quarters majority vote, thus clarifying the decision-making process under the convention.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2011-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Describing the proposal as "intriguing", Black noted that although it would theoretically enable developing countries to use their numerical superiority to adopt any kind of world-wide binding obligation, in practical terms they would still need the approval of rich countries to secure funding.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2011-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Xie said that he was concerned about the reluctance of developed nations to reduce their own greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2011-united-nations-climate-change-conference] He called on developed countries to provide financial and technical aid to help developing nations fight against and cope with the effects of climate change.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2011-united-nations-climate-change-conference] India's representative at the conference, Jayanthi Natarajan stated that India "will not be intimidated.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2011-united-nations-climate-change-conference] There is an attempt to shift the blame to developing countries.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2011-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Bruce Campbell, Director of the CGIAR research program on Climate Change, Agriculture and Food Security (CCAFS), said it was astonishing that agriculture, one of the worst emitters of greenhouse gases, remained excluded from global agreements on climate change.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2011-united-nations-climate-change-conference] "Leading agricultural groups, from farmers and researchers to policymakers and development organisations, have all come together to call on COP17 negotiators to address the need for a Work Programme on agriculture", Campbell said.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2011-united-nations-climate-change-conference] "Now, it is up to negotiators to heed our joint call-to-action and allow agriculture to play its part in building resilience amongst vulnerable populations, helping farmers adapt to more unpredictable and extreme weather conditions and mitigating future climate change".
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2011-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Nnimmo Bassey, Chair of Friends of the Earth International, said "delaying real action until 2020 is a crime of global proportions ...
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2011-united-nations-climate-change-conference] An increase in global temperatures of 4 degrees Celsius, permitted under this plan, is a death sentence for Africa, Small Island States, and the poor and vulnerable worldwide.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2011-united-nations-climate-change-conference] After two weeks of negotiations a deal was reached only on the last day, Sunday 11 December, after a 60-hour marathon negotiation session.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2011-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Negotiators agreed to be part of a legally binding treaty to address global warming.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2011-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The terms of the future treaty were to be defined by 2015 and become effective in 2020.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2011-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The agreement, referred to as the "Durban Platform for Enhanced Action", was notable in that for the first time it included developing countries such as China and India, as well as the US which had refused to ratify the Kyoto Protocol.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2011-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The agreement entailed the continuation of the Kyoto Protocol in the interim, although only some countries including members of the EU were indicated as likely to commit.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2011-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The terms of the Durban Platform were ultimately met following the successful negotiation of the Paris Agreement at the 2015 United Nations Climate Change Conference in Paris, France.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2011-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The conference led to agreement on a management framework for a future Green Climate Fund.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2011-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The fund is to distribute US$100bn per year to help poor countries adapt to climate impacts.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2011-united-nations-climate-change-conference] After the conference concluded, Michael Jacobs of the Grantham Research Institute on Climate Change and the Environment in London, said: "The agreement here has not in itself taken us off the 4 °C path we are on...
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2011-united-nations-climate-change-conference] But by forcing countries for the first time to admit that their current policies are inadequate and must be strengthened by 2015, it has snatched 2 °C from the jaws of impossibility.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2011-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Christiana Figueres, executive secretary of the UN Framework Convention on Climate Change said: "I salute the countries who made this agreement.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2011-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Kumi Naidoo of Greenpeace International said: "Right now the global climate regime amounts to nothing more than a voluntary deal that's put off for a decade.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2011-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Inhofe said that the message from Washington, including from President Obama and the Democratic leadership of the U.S.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2011-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Senate, to the delegates of the conference was that they are being ignored.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2011-united-nations-climate-change-conference] German media criticised the outcome as "almost useless", saying the pledges are vague and the timeline is slow, the main merit being that the talks have been kept alive.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2012-canadian-federal-budget] The **Canadian federal budget** for fiscal year 2012–13 was presented to the House of Commons of Canada by Finance Minister Jim Flaherty on 29 March 2012.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2012-canadian-federal-budget] Among the most notable elements of the federal budget were changes to Old Age Security and a reduction of the budget for the Canadian Forces and the Canadian Broadcasting Corporation.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2012-canadian-federal-budget] The budget presentation was also used to announce that the penny would no longer be minted as of late 2012.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2012-canadian-federal-budget] As a result of the budget, in April 2012 the CBC announced it would cut its English Services budget by $86 million, of which $43 million was a reduction of programming and the remainder the elimination of 256 jobs.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2012-canadian-federal-budget] It said it would also cut jobs in other departments, totalling 650 throughout the corporation.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2012-canadian-federal-budget] It cancelled the TV series *InSecurity* and the television program *Connect with Mark Kelley*.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2012-canadian-federal-budget] The changes included a reduction of the budget for CBC News by $10 million, the elimination of 88 jobs in that division, and the shuttering of its news bureaus in South America and Africa.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2012-canadian-federal-budget] CBC Radio had its budget reduced by $3 million, eliminated 18 jobs, and stated it would no longer commission radio dramas.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2012-canadian-federal-budget] Other programming cuts included the radio program *Dispatches* and CBC Sports, which had a $4 million budget reduction and recast *Sports Weekend* as a seasonal program.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2012-canadian-federal-budget] Agriculture and Agri-Food Canada announced in April 2012 that it would close the Cereal Research Centre operated at the University of Manitoba.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2012-canadian-federal-budget] The Public Service Alliance of Canada (PSAC) stated that 5,561 of its members in 23 government departments had received notices from the federal government about the potential termination of their jobs.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2012-canadian-federal-budget] This includes 308 jobs at the Canadian Food Inspection Agency, which will cut its operating budget by $56 million.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2012-canadian-federal-budget] The Professional Institute of the Public Service of Canada announced that the employment of 1,500 of its members would be affected.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2012-canadian-federal-budget] Health Canada would eliminate up to 840 jobs, including 150 scientists.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2012-canadian-federal-budget] The Department of National Defence will cut at least 1,149 public service jobs, about 585 of which are in the Canadian Forces and 234 at the Defence Research and Establishment Canada.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2012-canadian-federal-budget] Library and Archives Canada is expected to eliminate 105 jobs, and Statistics Canada is expected to cut 273.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2012-canadian-federal-budget] In November 2012, the Treasury Board president Tony Clement stated that the federal government had cut 10,980 public service jobs, of which 7,500 were by attrition or not replacing employees who had quit.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2012-canadian-federal-budget] The Canadian government has introduced measures to encourage business to invest in the Canadian economy.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2012-canadian-federal-budget] There were five federal corporate tax cuts over a period of five years with the last 1.5 percent reduction taking effect on 30 December 2011, bringing the federal corporate tax to 15 per cent.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/2012-canadian-federal-budget] This budget was criticized because of cuts to health care, the old age security, environmental protection and because of the expansion of $6 billion in corporate tax cuts for corporations, banks, and oil companies.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The **41st Canadian Parliament** was in session from June 2, 2011 to August 2, 2015, with the membership of its House of Commons having been determined by the results of the 2011 federal election held on May 2, 2011.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] It was dissolved prior to the 2015 federal election.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] Parliament convened on June 2, 2011, with the election of Andrew Scheer as Speaker, followed the next day with the Speech from the Throne.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] On August 2, 2015, Prime Minister Stephen Harper asked the Governor General to dissolve Parliament and issue the writ of election, leading to an 11-week election campaign period for the 2015 federal election.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] Significant legislation adopted during the 41st Parliament included the *Copyright Modernization Act*, the *Safe Streets and Communities Act*, the *Jobs, Growth and Long-term Prosperity Act*, the *Jobs and Growth Act* and the *Fair Elections Act*.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The orange wave during the 2011 election saw a surge in support for the New Democratic Party.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] This resulted in them becoming the official opposition for the first time in the country's history, as well as marking the Liberal party's first time not taking first or second place in a Canadian election.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] Jack Layton was the Leader of the Opposition until his death on August 11, 2011.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] Nycole Turmel followed as the party's interim leader until Tom Mulcair won the 2012 leadership election.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The parliament's first session ran between June 2, 2011, and September 13, 2013, and saw 83 bills adopted.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] In June 2011, immediately following the election the first six bills were given royal assent.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] When the parliament re-convened in September 2011, the Minister of Justice introduced the *Safe Streets and Communities Act* (Bill C-10), an omnibus bill of nine separate measures.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The bill was reviewed by the 'House Standing Committee on Justice and Human Rights' throughout October and November, chaired by Oxford MP Dave MacKenzie and passed by the House of Commons on December 5, 2011, on a 157 to 127 vote, with only the Conservative Party voting in favour.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The senate made six amendments and it was given royal assent on March 13, 2012.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] On September 29 the Minister of Industry introduced the *Copyright Modernization Act* (Bill C-11]) — the same bill that was introduced in the 3rd session of the previous parliament and referred to the 'Legislative Committee on Bill C-32'.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The bill finally passed the House of Commons on June 18 and given royal assent on June 29.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The Minister of Agriculture introduced the *Marketing Freedom for Grain Farmers Act* (Bill C-18) which repealed the *Canadian Wheat Board Act*, eliminating the requirement for farmers to sell wheat and barley produce to the Canadian Wheat Board.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The new act also appoints a new board of directors that must either privatize or dismantle the wheat board.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The bill was studied by the 'Legislative Committee on Bill C-18' chaired by Wetaskiwin MP Blaine Calkins between October 31 and November 4.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] A federal trial court decided that for the bill to be legal the government required the consent of the affected farmers, via a vote or plebiscite, as provided for in the 1998 *Canadian Wheat Board Act*, although that case is in appeal as of December 2011.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] Nevertheless, on November 28, the bill was passed by the House of Commons, with only the Conservative Party voting in favour.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The bill was reviewed by the Standing Senate Committee on Agriculture and Forestry in December and passed by the Senate on December 15, 2011.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] Despite the ruling of the judicial branch, Governor General David Johnston gave royal assent to the bill on the same day.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The registration of long guns had been a divisive issue since its inception in 1995.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The bill was introduced on October 25 and reviewed by the 'House Standing Committee on Public Safety and National Security' throughout November, chaired by Crowfoot MP Kevin Sorenson.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] With no amendments made to the bill in committee, it was passed on February 15 by the House of Commons on a 159 to 130 vote, with only two opposition MPs voting in favour.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The bill was passed by the senate on April 5, 2012, and given royal assent the next day.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The Minister of Public Safety also introduced the *Protecting Children from Internet Predators Act* (Bill C-30) which proposed to amend the Criminal Code to grant law enforcement agencies new powers, such as online surveillance or warrantless wiretapping, to combat criminal activity on the internet.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The bill has met with criticism from privacy groups, opposition MPs and the public over charges that the law would infringe on the privacy rights of Canadian citizens.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] Toews responded to the opposition by stating, addressing a Liberal MP, "He can either stand with us or stand with the child pornographers" which was received negatively.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The bill was introduced on February 14, 2012, and declared dead a year later when the *Response to the Supreme Court of Canada Decision in R. v.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] Tse Act* (Bill C-55) was introduced which also makes provisions for online surveillance and warrantless wiretapping.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] Senate leader Majorly LeBreton introduced the *Safe Food for Canadians Act* (Bill S-11) which was part of a response to tainted meat being discovered coming from the XL Foods processing plant in September 2012.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The act made numerous changes to the food regulatory system, including requiring better tracking of products, providing food inspectors more authority and increasing penalties for violations.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The Minister of Justice introduced the *Not Criminally Responsible Reform Act* (Bill C-54) on February 8, 2013.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The legislation proposes to create a "high risk" designation for people found guilty of a crime but not criminally responsible due to a mental disorder and enshrines in law that the safety of the public is paramount in deciding whether and how such a person can re-enter society.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] On April 26, 2012, the Minister of Finance introduced the *Jobs, Growth and Long-term Prosperity Act* (Bill C-38), an omnibus bill that amends over 50 laws.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] It creates a new department called Shared Services Canada and replaces the Employment Insurance Board of Referees with the Social Security Tribunal.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The bill also provides for moving the Old Age Security pension threshold from 65 to 67 years old, and provides for the deprecation of the penny and social insurance number cards.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The government was criticized for limiting debate on the 420-page bill to only seven days.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The bill was passed by the House of Commons on June 18 and the Senate on June 29 and given royal assent on the same day.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The second omnibus bill was the *Jobs and Growth Act* (Bill C-45), introduced on October 18, 2012, by the Minister of Finance and adopted on December 14.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The 443-page bill makes 65 amendments to 24 laws.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The portion of the bill that dealt with political pensions was taken out after first reading and re-introduced as the *Pension Reform Act* (Bill C-46).
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] Fifteen private member bills had received royal assent.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The second session ran between October 16, 2013, and August 2, 2015, and saw 86 bills receive royal assent.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The *Prohibiting Cluster Munitions Act* implemented Canada's commitments made under the Convention on Cluster Munitions.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The *Canadian Museum of History Act* changed the name and purpose of the Canadian Museum of Civilization to the Canadian Museum of History.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The *Combating Counterfeit Products Act* created a new criminal offence for possessing or exporting of counterfeit goods and allows customs officers to detain goods that they suspect infringe copyright or trade-marks.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The *Red Tape Reduction Act* required that a federal government regulation be eliminated for every new regulation created affecting a business.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The Minister of Aboriginal Affairs introduced the *First Nations Elections Act* which created an alternative electoral system, to the system under the *Indian Act*, that First Nations may opt in to elect chiefs and councils.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The Minister of Justice sponsored seven bills.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The *Protecting Canadians from Online Crime Act* made revenge porn illegal.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The *Tackling Contraband Tobacco Act* created a new criminal offence for selling, distributing or delivering contraband tobacco products.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The *Not Criminally Responsible Reform Act* makes those found guilty of an offense but not criminally responsible be deemed high risk offenders.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The *Victims Bill of Rights Act* creates the "Canadian Victims Bill of Rights" and provides for a right to present a victim impact statement, a right to the protection of identity, a right to participate in the criminal justice process and a right to seek restitution.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The *Justice for Animals in Service Act* makes it a criminal offense to kill or injure a law enforcement animal or a military animal while the animal is carrying out its duty.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The Minister of Public Safety sponsored four bills.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The *Protection of Canada from Terrorists Act* allows Canadian Security Intelligence Service (CSIS) to act outside Canadian borders, share information with foreign intelligence agencies and guarantee anonymity to informants.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The *Anti-terrorism Act, 2015* makes promoting terrorism a criminal offense, allows for preventative arrests, allows for easier information sharing, inclusive of confidential data, between federal organizations for the purpose of detecting threats, and providing new powers to CSIS.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The *Common Sense Firearms Licensing Act* simplifies firearms licensing, provides a six-month amnesty for renewing a licence, eases rules on transporting restricted guns, provides the cabinet power to classify guns, and creates new limits to the power of the chief firearms officer.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The *Drug-Free Prisons Act* gives the Parole Board of Canada permission to cancel parole after a positive drug test.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The Minister of Health's *Respect for Communities Act* requires extensive consultation and letters of approvals to allow supervised injection site like Insite.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The same minister also introduce the *Safe and Accountable Rail Act* establishes minimum liability insurance levels for railway companies and creates a new compensation fund financed by shippers for use to cover damages from railway accidents.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] Nineteen private member bills were adopted in the second session.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] In total during the 41st Parliament, Prime-Minister Harper appointed 21 senators, all of whom caucused with the Conservative Party.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] On May 18, 2011, two weeks after the election, Harper appointed Fabian Manning, Larry Smith, and Josée Verner, all of whom were defeated Conservative Party candidates in the general election.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] Manning and Smith had resigned from the Senate to run in the election and they became the first Senators to be reappointed to the Senate since John Carling in April 1896.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] A third batch of senators were appointed on September 6, 2012.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] They included the first Vietnamese-Canadian, Thanh Hai Ngo, and the first Filipino-Canadian, Tobias C.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] Enverga, to be appointed as senators, as well as Diane Bellemare of Montreal, Tom McInnis of Halifax, and Paul McIntyre.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] In early 2013, Harper appointed a final batch, including Denise Batters, David Wells of St.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] John's, Victor Oh of Mississauga, Lynn Beyak of Dryden, Ontario, plus Alberta Senators-in-waiting Doug Black and Scott Tannas.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] Of those who left the Senate during the 41st Parliament, 22 had reached the mandatory retirement age, including 12 Conservative Party members and one of the two remaining Progressive Conservatives.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] Three senators (Fred Dickson, Doug Finley, and Pierre Claude Nolin) died while in office.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] Of the remaining, 13 voluntarily resigned for various reasons, including 7 who had caucused with the Liberal Party and 6 with the Conservative Party.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] A comprehensive audit of all senator expenses was released in June 2015 which identified 21 senators who claimed and were paid for invalid expenses, amounting to $978,627.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] In addition to Duffy, Wallin, Brazeau and Harb, the audit recommended criminal investigations be conducted into the expense claims of 9 other senators who had served during the 41st Parliament.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] In January 2014, the Liberal Party removed its senate members from its national party caucus.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] From then on, the members and the new senate caucus were referred to as "Independent Liberal" and referred to themselves as the "Senate Liberal Caucus", though they were no longer formally affiliated with the Liberal Party of Canada.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] Five ministers were lost in the election to retirement or defeat.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] In the 18 May cabinet shuffle Harper promoted Steven Blaney, Ed Fast, Joe Oliver, Peter Penashue to ministerial positions, as well as promoting Denis Lebel and Julian Fantino from Minister of State roles to ministerial positions.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] He also promoted Bernard Valcourt, Tim Uppal, Alice Wong, Bal Gosal, and Maxime Bernier to Minister of State roles, replacing the two who had been promoted to Minister, one who had been defeated in the election, and Rob Merrifield and Rob Moore who were demoted.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] Upon the retirement of Bev Oda in July 2012, Harper promoted Julian Fantino to replace her as Minister for International Cooperation, with Bernard Valcourt replacing Fantino as Associate Minister.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] In preparing for the second session, Harper shuffled his cabinet in July 2013.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] Kellie Leitch, Chris Alexander, Shelly Glover and Kerry-Lynne Findlay were promoted to ministerial positions.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] Vic Toews, Keith Ashfield, Peter Kent and Gordon O'Connor were removed from cabinet.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] Michelle Rempel, Pierre Poilievre, Greg Rickford, Candice Bergen and Rob Moore were promoted from Parliamentary Secretaries to Ministers of State.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] Kevin Sorenson was added to cabinet as a Minister of State.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] John Duncan resigned as Minister of Aboriginal Affairs and Northern Development a couple months previously but was added back into cabinet as a Minister of State.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] In the shuffle Leona Aglukkaq became the new Minister of Environment, Rona Ambrose the new Minister of Health, Rob Nicholson the new Minister of National Defence, Gail Shea the new Minister of Fisheries and Oceans, and Peter MacKay the new Minister of Justice and Attorney-General.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] The current and former officers of Parliament during the 41st Parliament are set out below.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] Resigned to accept a position in the private sector.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] Resigned to spend more time with his family and join the private sector.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/41st-canadian-parliament] Resigned to run again in a by-election following election spending concerns.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/abbotsford-police-department] The **Abbotsford Police Department** (**APD**; French: *Service de police d'Abbotsford*) is the police force for the City of Abbotsford, British Columbia, Canada.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/abbotsford-police-department] The force was established in 1955 as the Matsqui Police Department and was renamed the Abbotsford Police Department when Matsqui and Abbotsford amalgamated in 1995 to become the City of Abbotsford.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/abbotsford-police-department] The vision of the Abbotsford Police Department is to have the "Strength in Community".
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/abbotsford-police-department] The mission of the Abbotsford Police Department is "make Abbotsford the safest city in BC".
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/abbotsford-police-department] The force is divided into six branches: patrol, criminal investigation, finance and budget, human resources, operations support, and support services.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/abbotsford-police-department] The organization has 216 sworn officers, 84 civilians and over 100 volunteers, according to the police board and 2011 Abbotsford Police Department Compstat reports.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/abbotsford-police-department] Since its founding in 1955, the APD has had two policemen killed in the line of duty.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/agriculture-and-agri-food-canada] The minister of agriculture and agri-food is responsible for the department to Parliament.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/agriculture-and-agri-food-canada] While the minister is head of the department, and provides policy/political direction, the day-to-day operations of the department are managed by the deputy minister, who is a public servant.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/agriculture-and-agri-food-canada] The Department of Agriculture for Canada was formed in 1867.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/agriculture-and-agri-food-canada] It was organized under the *Department of Agriculture Act*, which was passed by Parliament and given royal assent on 22 May 1868.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/agriculture-and-agri-food-canada] The first minister of agriculture, Jean-Charles Chapais, and his deputy, Dr.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/agriculture-and-agri-food-canada] Joseph Charles Taché, were soon presenting important bills to the House of Commons for the protection and improvement of Canadian agriculture.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/agriculture-and-agri-food-canada] One of the first bills was an *Act Respecting Contagious Diseases of Animals*, passed in 1869.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/agriculture-and-agri-food-canada] This law gave the chief veterinary inspector, Dr.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/agriculture-and-agri-food-canada] Duncan McEachran, who was also the dean of medicine at McGill University, authority to prevent the introduction of animal diseases into Canada.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/agriculture-and-agri-food-canada] In addition to agriculture, the minister and the department had many other wide-ranging national responsibilities including immigration, public health, censuses and statistics, patents, copyrights, and trademarks.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/agriculture-and-agri-food-canada] Over time, these other responsibilities were transferred to other departments.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/agriculture-and-agri-food-canada] For example, the collection of statistics was transferred to the Dominion Bureau of Statistics (now Statistics Canada) in 1918, and healthcare in Canada was transferred to the Department of Health when it was created in 1919.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/agriculture-and-agri-food-canada] In 2013, the Canadian Food Inspection Agency was moved from the Agriculture Portfolio to the Health Portfolio.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/agriculture-and-agri-food-canada] Agriculture and Agri-Food Canada is responsible for a number of laws related to agriculture and food in Canada.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/agriculture-and-agri-food-canada] It is also in the Branch's mandate to provide scientific information to inform departmental and governmental decision processes.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/agriculture-and-agri-food-canada] Under the *Experimental Farm Stations Act* dating back to 1886, farm stations across Canada were established, including the Central Experimental Farm.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/agriculture-and-agri-food-canada] The officers of these stations had the duty of conducting research in a number of specific areas pertinent to agricultural productivity and conservation, and of making the results of such research known by publication.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/agriculture-and-agri-food-canada] Today, the Science and Technology Branch includes a national network of 20 Research and Development Centres and 30 satellite research locations.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/agriculture-and-agri-food-canada] The Science and Technology Branch has approximately 2,200 employees, including some 400 research scientists.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/agriculture-and-agri-food-canada] Agriculture and Agri-Food Canada is also responsible for supporting corporate and local agricultural producers and suppliers.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/agriculture-and-agri-food-canada] They do this through a variety of programs and services including Agri-Geomatics which develops products and services for internal and external users, and program facilitation.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/agriculture-and-agri-food-canada] The department supports market growth through its market access and trade negotiation activities, and it works with Canada's provinces and territories to promote Canadian products.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/agriculture-and-agri-food-canada] The department also supports industry by focusing on science and technology advances and helping producers mitigate risks.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/agriculture-and-agri-food-canada] Agrivoltaics, also known as agro-photovoltaics, is the practice of using the same land for both solar energy production and agriculture.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/agriculture-and-agri-food-canada] This system places solar panels above crops or pastures, allowing sunlight to generate electricity while still supporting plant growth underneath.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/agriculture-and-agri-food-canada] This approach helps farmers make more efficient use of their land, especially in areas where space is limited.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/agriculture-and-agri-food-canada] Agrivoltaic systems can also protect crops from extreme weather, reduce water evaporation, and sometimes even increase crop yields by creating a cooler, shaded microclimate.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/agriculture-and-agri-food-canada] In places like Canada, studies have shown that using just 1% of farmland for agrivoltaics could provide up to one-third of the country’s electricity needs, all while continuing food production.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/air-quality] Outdoor air pollution comes from burning fossil fuels for electricity and transport, wildfires, some industrial processes, waste management, demolition and agriculture.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/air-quality] Indoor air pollution is often from burning firewood or agricultural waste for cooking and heating.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/air-quality] Other sources of air pollution include dust storms and volcanic eruptions.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/air-quality] Many sources of local air pollution, especially burning fossil fuels, also release greenhouse gases that cause global warming.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/air-quality] However, air pollution may limit warming locally.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/air-quality] Air pollution kills 7 to 8 million people each year.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/air-quality] It is a significant risk factor for a number of diseases, including stroke, heart disease, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), asthma, coronavirus and lung cancer.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/air-quality] Particulate matter is the most deadly, both for indoor and outdoor air pollution.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/air-quality] Ozone affects crops, and forests are damaged by the pollution that causes acid rain.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/air-quality] Overall, the World Bank has estimated that welfare losses (premature deaths) and productivity losses (lost labor) caused by air pollution cost the world economy over $8 trillion per year.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/air-quality] Various technologies and strategies reduce air pollution.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/air-quality] Key approaches include clean cookers, fire protection, improved waste management, dust control, industrial scrubbers, electric vehicles and renewable energy.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/air-quality] National air quality laws have often been effective, notably the 1956 Clean Air Act in Britain and the 1963 US Clean Air Act.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/air-quality] International efforts have had mixed results: the Montreal Protocol almost eliminated harmful ozone-depleting chemicals, while international action on climate change has been less successful.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/elimination-of-toxics] The **Accelerated Reduction/Elimination of Toxics** (ARET) program was a Canadian program established in the early 1990s with the goal of using voluntary measures to reduce or eliminate harmful substances.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/elimination-of-toxics] The program was started by the New Directions Group (NDG), a group of senior industry representatives and Environmental Non-Government Organizations (ENGOs).
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/elimination-of-toxics] After Environment Canada formally supported the initiative in 1991, the ARET Stakeholder committee was formed to participate in the program.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/elimination-of-toxics] The committee consisted of representatives from industry, provincial and federal governments, health and environmental groups, and labour organizations.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/elimination-of-toxics] The committee first evaluated a list of over 2,000 chemicals, scoring them on the basis of toxicity, persistence, and bioaccumulation capability.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/elimination-of-toxics] By 1994, the evaluation was complete and a resulting list of 117 toxic substances were slated by the committee for voluntary elimination or reduction by the year 2000.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/elimination-of-toxics] The success of the ARET program is disputed.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/elimination-of-toxics] While Environment Canada states that over 70,000 tonnes of toxic substances were prevented from release because of the success of the program, the multi-stakeholder nature of the committee lead to disagreements over which substances would be given priority.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/elimination-of-toxics] Environmental and labour groups withdrew from the committee over the emphasis placed on *reductions*, rather than *eliminations*, of these substances by industry representatives.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/elimination-of-toxics] Nils Axel Braathen also claims that knowing to what extent the reductions were actual improvements from the "business-as-usual" reduction scenario is very difficult, meaning that the net environmental benefits were questionable.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] Under the Constitution of Canada, responsibility for environmental management in Canada is a shared responsibility between the federal government and provincial governments.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] For example, provincial governments have primary authority for resource management including permitting industrial waste discharges (e.g., to the air).
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] The federal government is responsible for the management of toxic substances in the country (e.g., benzene).
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] The department provides stewardship of the Environmental Choice Program, which provides consumers with an eco-labelling for products manufactured within Canada or services that meet international label standards of (GEN) Global Ecolabelling Network.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] Under the *Canadian Environmental Protection Act* (CEPA 1999) (R.S., 1999, c.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] 33), ECCC became the lead federal department to ensure the cleanup of hazardous waste and oil spills for which the government is responsible, and to provide technical assistance to other jurisdictions and the private sector as required.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] The department is also responsible for international environmental issues (e.g., Canada-US air issues).
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] CEPA was the central piece of Canada's environmental legislation but was replaced when budget implementation Bill C-38 entered into effect in June 2012.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] "Recognizing the need for better environmental management, the federal government passed the *Canada Water Act* in 1970 and created the Department of the Environment in 1971, entrusting the Inland Waters Directorate with providing national leadership for freshwater management.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] Under the *Constitution Act*, *1867*, the provinces are "owners" of the water resources and have wide responsibilities in their day-to-day management.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] The *Canada Water Act* (proclaimed on September 30, 1970) provides the framework for cooperation with provinces and territories in the conservation, development, and utilization of Canada's water resources.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] The *Canadian Environmental Protection Act*, 1999, completes the framework for the protection and of water resources.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] Environment and Climate Change Canada is the federal department in charge of conserving and protecting Canada's water resources.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] The *Water Act* (2000), a federal legislation, "supports and promotes the conservation and management of water, including the wise allocation and use of water.".
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] The provinces are responsible for administering the *Water Act* (2000).
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] In Alberta for example, Alberta Environment and Water is responsible for administering the *Water Act* (2000) and the *Environmental Protection and Enhancement Act* (2000).
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] Provinces environmental ministries primarily lead Water for Life (2003) programs.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] The 1997 Kyoto Accord caused Minister David Anderson and the Chretien government to launch the *Government of Canada Action Plan 2000 on Climate Change*, which was mentioned in passing by the Governor-General in her January 30, 2000 Speech from the Throne.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] Despite strong objections from the governments of Saskatchewan, Alberta and Ontario and the federal Official Opposition, in securing Canadian ratification of the Kyoto Protocol in December 2002.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] In 2004 Anderson was successful in getting the Species at Risk Act passed by Parliament and signed into law.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] Other initiatives involved improving air and water quality and established improved federal provincial cooperation on environmental issues.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] The Durban talks were leading to a new binding treaty with targets for all countries to take effect in 2020.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] Kent argued that, "The Kyoto protocol does not cover the world's largest two emitters, the United States and China, and therefore cannot work." In 2010 Canada, Japan and Russia said they would not accept new Kyoto commitments.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] Canada is the only country to repudiate the Kyoto Accord.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] Kent argued that since Canada could not meet targets, it needed to avoid the $14 billion in penalties for not achieving its goals.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] This decision drew widespread international response.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] States for which the emissions are not covered by the Kyoto Protocol (the US and China) have the largest emissions, being responsible for 41% of the Kyoto Protocol.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] China's emissions increased by over 200% from 1990 to 2009 as canny industrialists moved there to avoid taxation.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] By 2011 the magnesium industry in Canada, which had been ranked second in 2000, had been regulated out of existence.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] Harper and Jim Flaherty's 2012 federal budget's *Jobs, Growth and Long-term Prosperity Act* replaced the *Canadian Environmental Assessment Act* (CEAA 1992, 1999) with the*Canadian Environmental Assessment Act*, 2012.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] By placing the emphasis on jobs, growth and prosperity significant changes have been made to the federal environmental assessment regime (EA) and environmental regulatory framework.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] In 2015, the newly elected Trudeau government changed the applied title of the department under the Federal Identity Program from *Environment Canada* to *Environment and Climate Change Canada*, in order to "reflect the government's priorities".
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] In early 2018, the government of Justin Trudeau passed the *Greenhouse Gas Pollution Pricing Act* (GHGPPA).
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] In early 2019, the government of Justin Trudeau passed the *Impact Assessment Act* and *Canadian Energy Regulator Act*s (IAA and CERA) under minister Catherine McKenna.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] On March 25, 2021, the Supreme Court of Canada rejected the 2019 appeal of the provinces of Alberta, Ontario, and Saskatchewan and ruled in *Reference re Greenhouse Gas Pollution Pricing Act* that the GHGPPA was constitutional.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] On April 6, 2022, Equinor's project on the Bay du Nord property was approved under Section 54 of the *Canadian Environmental Assessment Act, 2012* by the federal cabinet and Minister Guilbeault.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] The CEAA was used because the assessment was initiated before that law was voided by the IAA.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] The Impact Assessment Agency of Canada is an arms-length agency that reports to the Minister of Environment and Climate Change.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] Parks Canada, which manages the Canadian National Parks system, was removed from Environment Canada and became an agency reporting to the minister of Canadian heritage in 1998.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] In 2003, responsibility for Parks Canada was returned to the minister of the environment's portfolio.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] The Enforcement Branch is responsible for ensuring compliance with several federal statutes.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] Enforcement officers are appointed pursuant to section 217(3) of the *Canadian Environmental Protection Act*, having all the powers of peace officers.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] There are two designations of enforcement officers: Environmental Enforcement and Wildlife Enforcement.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] The former administers the *Canadian Environmental Protection Act* and pollution provisions of the *Fisheries Act* and corresponding regulations.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] The latter enforces *Migratory Birds Convention Act*, *Canada Wildlife Act*, *Species at Risk Act* and *The Wild Animal and Plant Protection and Regulation of International and Interprovincial Trade Act*.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] All officers wear dark green uniform with black ties and a badge (appear on the right).
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] Environmental Enforcement Officers only carry baton and OC spray whereas Wildlife Enforcement Officers are also equipped with firearm.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] The minister may also appoint members of the Royal Canadian Mounted Police, fishery officers, parks officers, customs officers and conservation officers of provincial and territorial governments as enforcement officers and to allow them to exercise the powers of Department of Environment officers.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] The Export and Import of Hazardous Waste and Hazardous Recyclable Material Regulations (EIHWHRMR) operates with a few basic premises, one of which being that electronic waste is either "intact" or "not intact".
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] Since Canada ratified the Basel Convention on August 28, 1992, and as of August 2011, the Enforcement Branch has initiated 176 investigations for violations under EIHWHRMR, some of which are still in progress.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] There have been 19 prosecutions undertaken for non-compliance with the provisions of the EIHWHRMR some of which are still before the courts.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] The department administers and assists in the administration of nearly c.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] The *Canada National Parks Act* governs Parks Canada Agency.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] The *Environmental Protection and Enhancement Act* (2000) "supports and promotes the protection, enhancement, and wise use of the environment.
[src:environment-and-climate-change-canada/environment-and-climate-change-canada] First enacted in 1917, the *Migratory Birds Convention Act* protects most species of birds in Canada through regulations surrounding hunting, culling, and scientific research.
